pull_request.title: Fixes part of #5345: Added Platform parameter overridding implementation.
pull_request.body:
Fixes part of #5345 :

This pull request introduces support for **local overrides of Platform Parameters** in the Developer Options dashboard. This enhancement allows developers to locally override platform parameter values for testing and debugging purposes, independent of remote values.

### Platform Parameter Enhancements

- UI now reflects overridden values distinctly within the platform parameter list (e.g., `PlatformParameterItemViewModel.kt`, `platform_parameters_item.xml`). 
- Added new string resources for displaying the overridden sync status (`untranslated_strings.xml`).

### Domain Logic Enhancements

- Updated `PlatformParameterControllerDebugImpl` to:
  - Maintain and persist local overrides via `LocalOverridePlatformParameterDatabase`. 
  - Ensure local overrides take precedence over remote values during ephemeral parameter resolution.
  - Support loading, updating, and clearing local overrides from persistent storage.
- Updated the platform parameter loading pipeline to prioritize local override values when available. 

### UI Interaction Improvements

- Added logic in `PlatformParametersFragmentPresenter` to:
  - Save  local overrides before leaving the screen.
  - Restore the correct UI state on rotation or re-entry.
  - Show the correct status indicator for overridden parameters.
  - Added new feild in the `arguments.proto` for storing the inavalid inputs.

### Testing Updates

- Extended tests in `PlatformParameterControllerDebugImplTest` to:
  - Validate that local overrides are correctly saved, prioritized, and retrieved.
  - Ensure that clearing overrides reverts back to remote/default values.
  - Include assertions for `SyncStatus.LOCAL_OVERRIDE`.
- Extended tests in `PlatformParametersFragmentTest` :
  - Added tests for override behaviour.
  - Added UI tests for the Alert Dialog.

### Updated `DrawableBindingAdapeter`

Added `.mutate()` in the binding adapter for better functuionality.

---

### Summary

These changes build upon the existing override infrastructure introduced for feature flags and extend it to platform parameters. By allowing local overrides with persistence, this work significantly improves the flexibility and efficiency of testing and debugging new platform parameter behavior.

issue.title: üóúÔ∏è Implement comprehensive compression and caching improvements (#358)
issue.body:
## üìä Overview
This PR implements advanced compression (Brotli) and fine-tuned caching strategies to reduce payload sizes and improve repeat visit performance, addressing Lighthouse findings from issue #358.

## üéØ What's Changed

### 1. **Build-Time Pre-Compression** üèóÔ∏è
- Added `vite-plugin-compression` to generate `.gz` and `.br` files during build
- Brotli compression at maximum quality (level 11)
- Only compresses files >1KB to avoid overhead

### 2. **Worker-Level Enhancements** ‚ö°
- Updated asset handler to serve pre-compressed files based on Accept-Encoding
- Added proper Vary headers for cache keying
- Fallback chain: Brotli ‚Üí Gzip ‚Üí Uncompressed

### 3. **Stale-While-Revalidate Implementation** üîÑ
- Enhanced cache middleware with SWR support
- Serves stale content instantly while revalidating in background
- Adds diagnostic headers for debugging (X-Cache-State, X-Cache-Revalidate)

### 4. **Optimized Cache Headers** üìã
- Immutable caching for hashed assets (1 year)
- SWR for images and dynamic content
- Proper cache partitioning by content type

### 5. **Cloudflare Configuration** ‚òÅÔ∏è
- Enabled `brotli_content_encoding` compatibility flag
- Created automation script for Compression Rules API
- Support for Zstandard on large files

## üìà Performance Impact

### Compression Results
| File Type | Gzip Reduction | Brotli Reduction | Brotli vs Gzip |
|-----------|---------------|-----------------|----------------|
| JavaScript | 65-84% | 68-86% | +3-6% better |
| CSS | 69-74% | 73-77% | +4-5% better |
| HTML | ~75% | ~80% | +5% better |

### Expected Improvements
- **Bandwidth**: 15-20% reduction vs gzip-only
- **Cache Hit Ratio**: >85% expected
- **TTFB**: Reduced through SWR and edge caching
- **CPU**: Zero runtime compression overhead

## üß™ Testing
- ‚úÖ Build generates compressed files correctly
- ‚úÖ Workers serve appropriate compressed variant
- ‚úÖ Cache headers properly configured
- ‚úÖ Vary headers prevent cache poisoning

## üìù Documentation
Created comprehensive documentation in `docs/decisions/compression-caching-improvements.md`

## üöÄ Deployment Steps
1. Merge PR
2. Deploy to preview environment
3. Run `./scripts/configure-compression.sh` with API credentials
4. Verify with Lighthouse audit

## ‚úÖ Checklist
- [x] Pre-compression working
- [x] Workers serving compressed assets
- [x] SWR cache implemented
- [x] Headers optimized
- [x] Documentation complete
- [x] Script for API configuration

## üîó Related
- Closes #358
- Follows recommendations from [Cloudflare Compression Docs](https://developers.cloudflare.com/speed/optimization/content/compression/)
- Implements [RFC 5861](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5861) for SWR

## üìä Lighthouse Impact
This should improve:
- Performance score (reduced transfer size)
- Best Practices (proper caching)
- Core Web Vitals (faster resource loading)

issue.title: feat: implement routing based on incoming SNI
issue.body:
Hi there,

Currently it is almost impossible to do routing with only one Inbound.

Of course, you can use Dokedomo-Door > Routing > Vless > Routing > Out, but in this case you will still have to have several INCOMING Dokedomo-Doors if I need to route traffic somewhere else.

Simple example:
> There is a server called TEST.
> We have VLESS Reality, which is configured according to all generally accepted standards on port 443, there is no Nginx/Haproxy/etc in front of it.
> 
> And here is the task: from the TEST server to route traffic to the TEST_B, TEST_C servers.
> This can be done quite simply, BUT then we will have two Inbound, and they cannot occupy port 443 at the same time.
> 
> On the other hand, we can put Nginx/Haproxy in front, as far as I know - putting something in front of Xray in the case of Reality is not recommended, from which I conclude that this method, although in theory it will be working, will be contrary to the principles of Reality.

This small PR adds the ability to define routing rules based on incoming SNI for Trojan+TLS, VLESS+Reality, VLESS+TLS.

With this routing, you will no longer need to create multiple inbounds on different ports if they are completely identical, and will also allow you to leave one single Reality on port 443 and at the same time have full routing capability based on SNI.

```
{
  "routing": {
    "rules": [
      {
        "type": "field",
        "incomingSni": ["domain:example.com", "sample.com"],
        "outboundTag": "BLOCK"
      }
    ],
    "domainStrategy": "AsIs"
  }
}
```
